<div>
	<h1>Dr Benjamin Schuster-B&ouml;ckler's Group</h1>
<div class="image_container left" style="width: 300px;"><img src="/_asset/image/benjamin-group.jpeg/fit/300/300/FF0000" alt="Benjamin group" /></div>
<h2><strong>Research Areas</strong></h2>
<p>&diams; Epigenetic effects on mutation rate variation in cancer genomes</p>
<p>&diams; Determinants of transcription factor binding specificity</p>
<p>&diams; Mechanisms of transcription regulation</p>
<p>&diams; Effects of alternative splicing in tumour formation</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2><strong>Research Overview</strong></h2>
<p align="justify">Our research group aims to shed light on the integration of signals that regulate gene expression in common cancers. Specifically, we are interested in the interplay between transcription factor binding and chromatin structure. In recent years, a number of key factors in the regulation of gene expression have emerged.</p>
<p align="justify">On the one hand, transcription factor proteins bind to specific regions of the genome where they can transiently act as activators or repressors. On the other hand, epigenetic marks affect broader regions where they can have long-lasting effects: DNA methylation on cytosine residues has been implicated in gene silencing. Finally, histone modifications are a diverse class of covalent modifications to the scaffolding protein around which DNA is wrapped inside the nucleus. They are thought to provide contextual information about the cell's state.</p>
<p align="justify">In our group, we aim to understand how these different biological signals are integrated. To do so, we take a "bottom-up" approach, starting from a small set of well-established signalling pathways in cancer such as the p53 pathway. The growing wealth of publicly available ChIP- and RNA-seq data allow us to track dynamic changes to the chromatin and transcription factor landscape. We now aim to use this information to quantify the relative contribution of sequence motifs and epigenetic marks on the target specificity of key transcription factors in cancer.</p>
<h2><strong>Key Publications</strong></h2>
<p align="justify"><strong>Schuster-B&ouml;ckler, B.</strong> &amp; Lehner, B. Chromatin organization is a major influence on regional mutation rates in human cancer cells.<em> Nature</em> 488, 504&ndash;507 (2012).</p>
<p align="justify"><strong>Schuster-B&ouml;ckler, B.,</strong> Conrad, D. &amp; Bateman, A. Dosage sensitivity shapes the evolution of copy-number varied regions. <em>PLoS ONE</em> 5, e9474 (2010).</p>
<p align="justify"><strong>Schuster-B&ouml;ckler, B.</strong> &amp; Bateman, A. Protein interactions in human genetic diseases. 9, <em>R9</em> (2008).</p></div>
